column5:
try staying close to park st for that night. if the grand hotel fits the bill, it is one the best possible locations for tourists looking to do and see stuff over a short period. always better to list your interests.
must eat at some of the restaurants on park street- peter cat (chelo kebab), mocambo (continental), bar b q (indian and chinese) and one step up (indian/conti). for a bit more authentic chinese, take a trip to tangra area- beijing, kafulok, golden joy.
for guwahati, try these places- chick n chilly for some lovely smoked chicken wraps. mughal garden serves some cracking beef kebabs etc. nagamese (2 outlets) for some outstanding pork with bamboo shoot and similar dishes. apologies if you are a vegetarian :d

spec, can't see past madinat dubai stay. middle east sure.
for short stay, normally szr world trade centre business bay central gets age range, jumeirah cluster hotels close mall emirates best fit round (disney style 'souk', waterpark, lots restaurants, bars beach too).
al maha desert wonderful allow children (i pretty sure) bab al shams - nice pool mini golf kids activities. desert resorts outside dubai rak ad quite long drives (qasr al sarab set wonderful dunes quite breathtaking) table.
shout need recommendations desert (a nice private bbq away crowds suggestion) private city tour? used organise events city contacts help out. blast!
column5:
for that spec, i can't really see past madinat for the dubai stay. you'll know you are in the middle east for sure.
for a short stay, i would normally suggest the szr from world trade centre to business bay as its about as central as it gets but i think for your age range, the jumeirah cluster of hotels close to mall of the emirates might be the best fit all round (disney style 'souk', waterpark, lots of restaurants, bars and its own beach too).
al maha in the desert is wonderful but they don't allow children (i am pretty sure) but bab al shams do - nice pool and they have mini golf and other kids activities. there are other desert resorts outside of dubai in rak and ad but they are quite long drives (qasr al sarab is set in wonderful dunes and is quite breathtaking) which might mean they are off the table.
shout if you need recommendations for desert (a nice private bbq away from the crowds would be my suggestion) and maybe a private city tour? used to organise events in the city so still have a few contacts that can help out. you'll have a blast!

column5:
hi
most of our stays at the beach were in the ground floor rooms, with their own terrace overlooking the palmito lawn... the corridor to them is near the ground floor exit heading to the beach after you come down the spiral staircase with the gold coloured handrail from reception ..room numbers beginning with the number 9.. nice little terrace with “ rock & swivel” ( very 1970’s ) chairs, a small table and a big sun umbrella.. these rooms are a bit bigger than standard rooms in the main block.
the 7th floor, which used to be the mushref bar is now the italian restaurant called “ sette”... it has its own listing on ta..although it wasn’t yet open the last time we were there.
the old italian, traviata, , was briefly converted into an arab/asian restaurant called “ phoenicia”, and we ate there a couple of times..... it was absolutely average... not impressed.. it’s listed as “ closed “ on ta.
one thing we really noticed on our last visit was that so many of the staff, who had become friends over the years were no longer there...miriam, who worked in the mushref bar, sunil, who ran the mushref bar, faith, who was the face of the peacock lounge for years, and who then moved on promotion to shooters, and was very successful there for her friendly approach and dedication to guest satisfaction, and sophia, who was a “ trainee “ in the ibn majid buffet restaurant when we first met her..
all those people were a huge asset to the hotel... we are fb friends with all of them, and several more, and all got the push when ja wanted to try and freshen up their style/customer facing profile when they tarted up the beach hotel.
what they did was sack a lot of their ( shall i say, “ more mature” ) staff and bring in a lot of new recruits who weren’t properly trained...
when i ask for a g&t in a bar, i don’t expect to be given a warm shot ( ?) glass, straight out of the glass washing machine, with a jug containing flat tonic water, and a saucer with 3 ice cubes and a slice of lemon..
i can do that at home...
in fact , it’s friday curry night, chez nous , so i’m heading to the fridge for some ice from dispenser, a wedge of lime, a can of fever tree cucumber, and a decent slug of bombay sapphire...
cheers folks..

column4:
@pankaj
i stayed dolphin nights couple years back. rooms large, beds comfortable, working ac, 24 hour hot water, flat screen tvs etc. clean, spic span - nothing intolerable. remember resorts staffed islanders find 'relaxed' service / cleanliness!
biggest positive right beach beach facing cottages direct sea view. unless planning spend lot time indoors (which highly unlikely - given number havelock). restaurant / dining hall clean menu simple - mostly vegetarian, non-veg available order. food alright.
location awesome plenty open spaces, benches, hammocks etc.to laze around. ideal sun rise view morning. booking hassle, online booking available rooms. value conscious traveler, it!
column5:
@pankaj
i have stayed in dolphin for 3 nights a couple of years back. rooms were large, beds comfortable, working ac, 24 hour hot water, flat screen tvs etc. it was clean, but not spic and span - but nothing intolerable. remember most resorts are staffed by islanders and you may find the same 'relaxed' service / cleanliness!
biggest positive is it is right on the beach and there are beach facing cottages that have direct sea view. unless you are planning to spend a lot of time indoors (which is highly unlikely - given the number of things to do in havelock). the restaurant / dining hall was clean and the menu was simple - mostly vegetarian, but non-veg available on order. food was alright.
location is awesome and has plenty of open spaces, benches, hammocks etc.to laze around. ideal for sun rise view in the morning. booking it is a hassle, but online booking is available for some of the rooms. if you are a value conscious traveler, go for it!

column5:
there used to be a good italian pizza place right on the grassmarket but i don’t remember if it was still there the last time i was down. there was however a small cafe that did us a very nice meal that time.
tbh, takeaways/cafes in that part of town seem to change hands pretty regularly and last couple of times, i was not that impressed with the current crop - choice or quality. the pubs are fairly consistent though. most have outdoor areas as well but i can’t say about takeaway.
laila’s at the top of cockburn st, a short walk away was an exception though - a small, good lebanese place. we have eaten there several times now and have not been disappointed. i think they also did takeaway and there are several other decent places that way - although the popularity of cockburn st means they tend to the pricier end of the scale.
the other way, towards lothian road and around the usher hall was also an island of small/independent places of varying types. probably because of the student accommodation nearby. places like this are being priced out of central edinburgh though - leith or further down leith walk and out beyond the meadows is where they seem to be relocating to.
edited: 8:30 am, august 07, 2021

'which days best fresh sushi london?' simple answer question.
given number restaurants takeaways prepare sell sushi, buyers supply chains, cooks wish prepare given day, seasonality fish dealt boat, availability fish wholesalers, transport time, asking something cannot determined.
column5:
'which days are best for fresh sushi in london?' there is no simple answer to that question.
given the number of restaurants and takeaways which prepare and sell sushi, their buyers and supply chains, what the cooks wish to prepare on any given day, the seasonality of the fish and how it's dealt with on the boat, availability of fish to wholesalers, transport time, and more you're asking for something that cannot be determined.

column5:
i think it's a worthwhile discussion! i've read that imperial club can be a bit of a scrum but clearly not everyone's experience! certainly when they (many years ago) used the old bar azure (i think that's what it was called!) as one of the places where you could get free drinks in the early evening, it meant it was suddenly packed, which really irritated me as it used to be our favourite place for a glass of champagne before dinner, listening to the piano player and feeding our children the little vegetable stick crudités that they handed out. so perhaps that's rather coloured my own view of ic...
but anyway... the ic lounge breakfast is advertised as 'continental' - we like saffron because, due to the time zone, we get up late, have a fairly substantial brunch, and that sees us through several hours in the waterpark. i'm personally a fan of the big vegetarian offering that they have (you can also get pork sausages and bacon if that's your thing). the dim sum is ok, there's lots of fruit, pastries, cereal - and yes even the massive chocolate fountain.
so depends what you want, but we tend to go big on breakfast and then not bother with lunch.
edited: 3:53 am, august 13, 2021

hi hanna, very true and opinions are all they are... but for some reason when i voice mine, which are very current and valid, they get reported and subsequently removed.
personally people trying to blame travelling to dubai for the current state of the uk covid rates is somewhat ridiculous and bizarre.
but, yes the palazzo versace is a great place. you really get that luxury vibe. afternoon tea was great, was in the main lobby area which is much more grand and luxurious than the executive club lounge. but, maybe because business is good right now they are moving it back to the club lounge from tomorrow. the club lounge drinks and food is from 6-8pm which is good. they had a decent f&b selection on offer. in fact the fox was gorgeous. an indian selection.
and the italian restaurant for dinner was lovely too, they had a couple of dancers, and a saxophonist playing also, which added to the vibe.
anyone in dubai for a special occasion should look into staying here for 2 or 3 nights.

the hotel is not that old only a few years so id be surprised if it was dated , the design is pretty neutral with a bit of arabian flare , you see a lot of the dark wood look in dubai - i like it and it feels warm and inviting . i thought the restaurants when we visited were very well styled esp the chinese /asian and the bistro . the rooms i liked and were large and light and we had a large balcony but we were at the front on the ground floor .
i havent returned only because i like the ghh in the marina and the jebel ali resort , but i would go back if the price was right , waldorf next door is supposed to be excellent , and i also fancy the anantara also on the palm. i think you can get some good prices for palm hotels and they are often nice resort style hotels. jumeriah zabeel is a big fav on here and comes in often at a good price.
id be mindful though with a date in may just in case it is still a red country listing . boris is going to have to be very careful how he lifts those restrictions on countries but id hope the uae would be one of the first , it cant compare to say brazil .

yeah, the name of hida folk village. people live in shirakawago but hida folk village is just a museum of folk houses.

nada, near kobe, is famous for producing hard water. so it is region which produce dry type.

fushimi , kyoto is producing milder type. if you just want to taste sake, you don't need to go to breweries but izakaya , japanese pub restaurants, will do. if you're interested in how they are produced, brewery tour will worth visiting. except the big factories type, sake is produced in the cold season because they are using mold, koji, which will go wrong in hot season.

column4: almost impossible booking restaurant. weeks away, let alone weekend. best bet talk campsite staff see local pubs walk ins service. advertised hit miss. major seaside towns plenty options terms fish chip vans, away pizza upmarket food vans evening stroll impromptu quayside picnic good option. otherwise, look bring cook simple barbecue whatever available. time matter pack macs weekend look brilliant, weather-wise.
column5: it is almost impossible to get a booking for a restaurant. even for weeks away, let alone this weekend. your best bet would be to talk to the campsite staff and see if any local pubs are doing a walk ins only service. this may not be advertised and will be hit and miss. the major seaside towns seem to have plenty of options in terms of fish and chip vans, take away pizza and some more upmarket food vans so an evening stroll with an impromptu quayside picnic can be a good option. otherwise, maybe look at what you can bring or cook for yourselves on a simple barbecue or whatever you have available. you will have a great time no matter what although pack the macs as this weekend does not look to be brilliant, weather-wise.

you’re moving around a lot; unpacking, packing, travelling. you’ll lose time with all the transfers. are you travelling with suitcases? you could leave your main luggage with your ubud accommodation and just have hand luggage for your island trips.
as suggested perhaps you could consider sanur for the last leg. there are cooking classes available. (i did my cooking class with janet de neefe of casa luna/indus fame in ubud which was excellent).
sanur has a lovely beachfront pathway with cafes, restaurants, markets. the main road, jalan danau tamblingan, has cafes, restaurants, bakeries, supermarket, shops. cycling is popular in sanur. beach is child friendly. you might enjoy a prahu boat ride. approximately half an hour to airport.

column5:
the sudemala resort is on seraya island which is 45 - 60 minutes from labuan bajo by boat.
labuan bajo is not the most attractive town on flores. within 15 years the once small fishing village has become a kuta-like place with a lot of facilities especially for tourists. the small town is full with hotels, restaurants (for some reason many italian restaurants), agents and projects. no nice beaches within the town itself (the most attractive ones are around 6 kms north of town). you could visit batu cermin, a cave in the northern part of town. at night there is a pasar kuliner (a foodmarket starting around 5 pm).
for a daytrip on the mainland of flores you’d better visit cunca wulang or cunca rami (waterfall) or lake sano nggoang or ruteng. even better a multiday overland trip.
the last time i was there was last year in april the town was empty, most restaurants and shops were closed.
regarding the tricky covid-situation in indonesia and the ever-changing reports about reopening, travelbubbles etc (and none of them came true untill now) we don’t know when everything will be back to normal again.
see also this article which means it will be very doubtful you can travel to flores in september.

column5: the telaga naga was a lovely restaurant in its day. the setting was stunning with lotus ponds surrounding the building, seeing it go to ruin was a shame. it closed its doors at the end of 2013 after serving chinese / asian food for over 30 years. twice a week they served an 'all you can eat buffet' which consisted of you ordering as many dishes as you wanted from the menu and cooked fresh.

column5:
if you have to fly into tokyo first, then i would change the order of visit so you don't have to face so many long train or bus rides after a long flight. spend the initial days at tokyo and work your way to kansai. at the end of your trip, fly out of osaka and go home via a tokyo airport transit if necessary.
ramen is everywhere. most places do a decent enough job. the ones that get very high marks often see long lines--not necessarily worth the effort.
sushi: i agree toyosu is not worth it at all. tsukiji outer market has sushi restaurants as well as other small eats. it's a much more interesting place to wander for 1/2 day. during normal times, it becomes very crowded after 10am so go early if you can. on average, i do find that even the chains around tsukiji serve slightly better quality items than some other places. of course, you can look at reviews and book some of the famous places at other parts of tokyo where quality and the whole experience could be better.
tokyo, osaka and other large cities also have very good places for yakiniku (grilled meat). be sure to try it a couple of times. you don't necessarily have to go for the top wagyu to enjoy the experience.
finally, december is iffy at best to visit at this point. a lot depends on the japanese vaccination rate by then but also whether japan feels foreign country visitors would bring in more cases. don't commit to anything if you can't get a refund.

column5:
as a born and bred londoner, it's nice to hear that people are keen to get back to the city i will always call home, no matter where in the world i might end up living!
i no longer live in london, but am lucky to live in a lovely town only 20 miles to the south...although being honest, at times my town is a bit too "lovely" for my liking and i find myself craving trips up to town. i'm lucky that we have reasonable train links into london, so since things have been opening up again i've made a point of setting saturdays aside so that i can jump on a train and go and explore familiar and some not so familiar sights. back in the noughties i spent a little over a year working in canary wharf, and i have to say that i wasn't a fan, to me is was a soulless concrete jungle (possibly not helped by not enjoying the job i was doing there!). but last saturday i decided to go and see if anything had changed, and was pleasantly surprised! for a saturday, the place was buzzing. people were out enjoying the bars, restaurants and malls, and generally strolling around in what was the start of a week-long heatwave. i particularly enjoyed watching the hot tub and bbq boats, a fairly new attraction where you and a group of friends hire a boat and either cook your own food on an onboard grill, or float around the docks in your own private hot tub (note that i am in no way affiliated with the company that provides this service, i just enjoyed seeing them!).
sometimes it takes being told your not allowed to do something to make you appreciate it all the more when you're finally allowed to again...hang in there!

column5:
i went to durham to see the cathedral on tuesday, july 6, and i wanted to share my experience with other would-be travelers.
-book the guided tour in advance. it was sold out for the day i went, and i had been waiting many years to visit the cathedral (romanesque architecture is my absolute favorite). it did not even occur to me that i needed to book many days in advance. i honestly thought i would cry when they kindly said it was sold out*. i texted my children and husband; my husband offered to try to find me a private tour guide immediately, but there was not way that could have worked out. very sweet of him, though.
-tour groups are currently limited to 5 or 6 ppl total. i was confused bc there was at least 1 large school group there on that day; many more than 5-6 ppl. i realize the rules come from the uk govt, not the cathedral. i realize that the cathedral is doing its best to follow what seem to be confusing rules (a big school group = ok, +6 adults in a tour group = not ok). it is what it is--just know them before you go.
-reserve a table in the cafe if you think you might eat there, or eat after 2pm.
*i did not cry, although i may never get to go to durham again (i live in tx), because of the volunteers at the cathedral. i would especially like to highlight hazel, a docent who was so helpful. she was like an angel. she answered my many questions in great detail and was the best of the british--kind, knowledgeable, and with a reserve that comes from a deep well of very good manners. she made me feel i could ask as many questions as i wanted to.
another female docent, tall, thin, with a sporty short haircut, encouraged me to buy a guidebook (which i did) and it was so helpful. many thanks to her.
it was a miserable day--chilly and pouring rain. a chipper younger woman at the entrance pointed out the river path to the bridge, and i'm so glad she did; it was a wonderful (although chilly) walk.
i arrived on a train from london; there is a bus that runs you to the cathedral every 15 minutes or so. many thanks to the women working in the station that day who pointed me in the right direction to catch the bus.
the bus driver was so nice and friendly. such an asset to durham and i'm sorry i did not make note of his name.
i had not eaten all day and, after seeing most of the cathedral, i went down to the cafe on a chance; there was 1 unreserved table at 2:15 (the guided tour started at 2). the women working in the cafe were very helpful. i had the lasagna special (lasagna, bread, and a salad) and a giant (hot and cozy) latte. my lunch was delicious and perfect for the weather.
there was a young, young woman in the gift shop; she was precious and sweet. the shop has a very good book on the architecture of the cathedral which i have been reading.
i wandered around the immediate area before catching the bus back to the train station and back to london. 6 hours on a train; 3 hours in durham.
all of the people i have referenced were at their posts after 12:20 on july 6. they deserve recognition. if there is any way to forward my thanks to them, please let me know.
the cathedral is exceptional and durham, even in the pouring rain, was charming. it was well worth the 3 hours there and 3 hours back on the train.
thank you, durham, for preserving this amazing unesco world heritage site and welcoming people so graciously and kindly. it's the graciousness and kindness i will most remember. and the lasagna. :)

column5:
i’ve not used luffield so can’t help there but..
you’ll find you spend a lot of time watching the race on the big screens (or your ipad) as well as what’s in front of you so a decent view of a screen is important - silverstone is pancake flat so seeing across the circuit is near impossible). high up won’t achieve much more viewing and puts you i bit further from the action, the win is that if it’s raining you’ll be drier and if it’s blazing sun there’s some shade - i doubt it matters but i’d want to be a dozen rows back from the front to cover weather extremes.
a f1 race is a relatively long event and there’s no natural ‘half time’ so from drivers parade to the end will take its toll on the bladders of the folk who go to the race with a few (or a lot of) beers (and there will be quite a few of them). if you sit at the end of a row you’ll be jumping up to let them visit the facilities with monotonous regularity, if you sit in the middle it will be a struggle if you get the call of nature. your choice!
ot, but if you want to watch a motor race rather than just ‘be there’ brands hatch offers a better viewing experience.

column5:
in 2015 we had a brilliant visit to japan, basing ourselves in tokyo and then kyoto around the beginning of the cherry blossom season, and visiting nikko, nara, hiroshima, hikone.
while there is no doubt loads more to see in both kyoto and tokyo, where would you recommend for a second visit? we'll be two adults, and we really enjoyed:
* travelling by train
* onsen
* japanese food
* historic buildings and sites
* gardens
* blossom
* the former tsukiji fish market
* tokyo art museums
we'd be looking at travelling in the autumn (probably no sooner than 2022 given covid, but it would be good to have something to look forward to) so we can see the autumn colour.
while we'd be flying from the uk, i'd prefer not to fly internally in japan if it can be avoided - so i wouldn't be looking to visit the far south and far north in one visit!
column8: Recommendations for a second visit to Japan

checking on agoda you can get deals at $1855 your budget for oasia for 7 nights feb 1-8. that’s about £8 above your budget per night.
from this location you’ve got a station on your doorstep, buses all around you, chinatown 10 mins walk and the absolutely incredible la pau sat also 10 mins walk away. you can walk to boat quay in about 25 mins. there’s tonnes of eateries galore and you’re in the thick of the city of singapore.
the hotel itself has a knockout swimming pool and another one indoors with an italian restaurant called osso which i’ve been to and reviewed favourably on tripadvisor.
you can also walk to marina bay from this location in 30 mins.
there’s tanjong pagar road as well which is full of korean and japanese food eateries.
i don’t think you can go wrong with this hotel and this location at so close to your budget.
the airport is on the same green line 40 mins door to door - no taxis or long walks needed!
good luck with whatever you decide

column5:
mira moon hotel, wan chai - excellent quarantine stay ... would highly recommend!
being stuck in the uk and uncertainty of when i was able to return due to flights being continuously cancelled, i had to change my check-in dates 11 times before i was able to return home and given this, my communication each time with mira moon was superb & seemless, with no questions asked or hassles and also accommodating pretty much all my requests.
the 3 weeks went relatively quickly as kept myself busy with exercise, and thankful for the large space of the full moon room, working and catching up with family and friends that helped pass the time. and not forgetting the free standing bath that was a welcoming luxury after the long runs i did in the room :) added to the experience, and were the standard amenities, were a nespresso machine (that led me to buy one as soon as i come out of quaranting!!) with "free-flow" capsules, small fridge (no freezer compartment), soaps and shampoo and ethernet connection & multiple usb ports.
having had to take full board as part of the quarantine package (which was all hotels), i can honestly say the food was excellent, with options of 'local touch', 'international' & 'vegetarian' where you could order from any type of cuisine in any one day, so the food was varied and tasty!
front desk service was always very curteous and prompt, including any outside deliveries from supermarket or care packages from friends around the world.
if i had to do it all again, i would more than likely stay at the mira moon again, though i don't plan to replicate the experiene any time soon!

column4:
people wat chaloem phra kiat prajomklao rachanusorn daytrip lampang, hour north. coming via 118 1252 half hours, used winding mountain roads here. driving lampang wat half hours. stairs long, getting top enjoying spectacular views reason go.
i plan night lampang, much see daytrip. drive visiting lamphun, perhaps mae tha market sai ua (northern sausage) kab moo plus nam prik (fried pork skin chili dip), explore lampang city. next morning wat chamloem head towards cm continue towards sukhothai,
column5:
most people do wat chaloem phra kiat prajomklao rachanusorn as a daytrip from lampang, maybe an hour north. coming via 118 and 1252 is more like 3 to 3 and half hours, especially if you are not used to the winding mountain roads here. driving first to lampang then to the wat is around 2 and half hours. the stairs are long, but getting to the top and enjoying the spectacular views is the reason to go.
i would suggest plan a night in lampang, too much to see and do for a daytrip. drive down visiting lamphun, perhaps mae tha market for sai ua (northern sausage) and kab moo plus nam prik (fried pork skin and chili dip), explore lampang city. next morning do wat chamloem and head back towards cm or continue on towards sukhothai,

hi everyone,
hoping to spend 3.5 weeks in thailand with my partner and 2 kids (6&8) in march/april 2022. i've visited a couple of times before but never with kids. want to keep travel time to a minimum and avoid long distances by road as the younger lad gets car sick esp in the heat. it's our first long haul trip.
would like a mix of affordable luxury accomm and budget options. we'd like to do some kid friendly sightseeing, shopping, nature and beaches- nothing too strenuous.
this is what i've planned so far and would be very grateful for any advice:
bangkok 4 nights centre point sukhumvit 10. sightseeing tour withlocals.com, snake farm and maybe siam park or similar in addition to some general wandering, eating, shopping etc.
sleeper to chiang mai (will book 1st class cabin in advance)
4-5 nights in cm, would love to stay at gaps house if family option available. elephant camp (day trip), night market, maybe cooking class.
fly to phuket and stay for approx 5 nights at centara grand karon
6 nights ko phi phi - phi phi the beach resort
back to phuket for the final week- katathani phuket beach resort. fly home from phuket.
i'm also interested in ko lanta but not sure how to fit in without a very long travel day and not a fan of packing up and moving too much with kids. re no of days my maths might be slightly off but you get the general idea :)
any thoughts, tips and advice greatly appreciated! thanks in advance

column5:
it’s a myth that fish has to be caught ‘same day’ to be best to eat
it depends on species / size and of course how long the fishing boat was at sea before the catch was landed, but some (especially larger) fish are better ‘hung’ before eating as sashimi.

column4:
glad asked! . first, left wednesday emirates flight jfk. lot anxiety, western ny regarding getting pcr test results time. finally place area opened kind owner assured results 36hrs shorter. monday test could sent sunday. overnite service sunday. test mon. morning results 6pm tuesday evening. flying jfk morning and, ugh, 12 hr layover jfk buffalo flight jfk now. able print problem. believe me, anxious! "calm" pcr testing place jfk, must lot customers, could used worse case scenario. calling person find turn time, etc. turn time 2hrs. results local test. fly pandemic wed. flight unless continue offer this, expensive, service jfk up.
ok, wrote buddies regarding jfk, felt survived zombie apocolypse. airport pitiful. people, many eating places closed. truly sad. people masking along w/ masking includes covering mouth, nose!
my flight uneventful. luckily window seat two seat next open. lot open seats people able stretch along four seats. food atrocious. vegetarian offer chicken offer. told crew horrible food was, wrote corporate email. said vegetarian selected option, offered option. said many people vegetarian missing fact needed request simple offer two choices. said, fault people can't read.
enjoyed dubai prepared sticker shock. travel poland food delicious, plentiful, fresh cheap. paid dubai, mind nice mall cafe, $21usd desert tea. bottle corona hotel $14usd. venture ethnic neighborhoods eat inexpensively.
didn't mention it, gardens (forgot official name) global village. enjoyed both. simple, stupid to. gardens nice two hours. global village , fun shopping, i'd allot 4-5hrs.
el fahidi favorite place. restored old part dubai typical shops it, nice atmosphere. liked souks. consider main entrance el fahidi, circle entrance thru parking lot, couple yards arabian tea house, street coffee cafe shops. shops man sells book bags, mugs, water holders, matted pictures name arabic script. is, imho, best shop uniqueness. made prc. free hand different colors. beautiful reasonable. mug $8usd, best souvenir shop dubai given pashimas, etc. india.
hope hotel near metro stop. said, lot walking dubai. helps. specifics, help you, answer.
column5:
glad you asked! . first, left on a wednesday emirates flight out of jfk. did have a lot of anxiety, being in western ny regarding getting a pcr test with results in time. finally a place in my area opened where the kind owner assured me of results in 36hrs or shorter. had to do on monday because the test could not be sent on sunday. no overnite service on sunday. so had the test mon. morning and did get the results around 6pm on tuesday evening. was flying to jfk in the morning and, ugh, had a 12 hr layover in jfk because buffalo has only one flight to jfk now. was able to print it an had no problem. believe me, i was anxious! only thing that did "calm" me was there is a pcr testing place at jfk, which i must say had a lot of customers, that i could have used in a worse case scenario. i was actually calling them in person to find out about turn around time, etc. the turn around time was maybe 2hrs. so i would have been ok if i didn't get the results of my local test. when i fly again in this pandemic i will probably not take a wed. flight unless they continue to offer this, expensive, service at jfk as a back up.
ok, so i wrote to some buddies of mine regarding jfk, i felt like i had survived a zombie apocolypse. the airport was pitiful. very few people, many eating places closed. it was truly sad. people were masking along w/ those who think masking includes just covering your mouth, not your nose!
my flight was uneventful. luckily i had a window seat and the two seat next to me open. there was a lot of open seats and some people were able to stretch out along four seats. the food was atrocious. one vegetarian offer and one chicken offer. i told the crew in the back how horrible the food was, even wrote corporate an email. i also said vegetarian is a selected option, not an offered option. they said too many people were vegetarian and missing the fact that they needed to request it so they simple offer it as one of two choices. i said, not my fault people can't read.
enjoyed dubai but be prepared for sticker shock. i like to travel to poland and food there is delicious, plentiful, fresh and cheap. i paid in dubai, mind you a nice mall cafe, $21usd for a desert and tea. a bottle of corona at the hotel was $14usd. i did venture out into the ethnic neighborhoods where you can eat inexpensively.
didn't mention it, but did go to the gardens (forgot the official name) and global village. enjoyed both. simple, stupid to get to. gardens are nice for two hours. global village , fun for shopping, i'd allot 4-5hrs.
el fahidi was my favorite place. its the restored old part of dubai with typical shops in it, but it does have a nice atmosphere. liked it more than the souks. in what i would consider the main entrance to el fahidi, off the circle entrance thru parking lot, just a couple yards from the arabian tea house, is a street that has a coffee cafe and a few shops. one of the shops the man sells book bags, mugs, water holders, matted pictures of your name in arabic script. this is, imho, the best shop because of its uniqueness. not made in prc. he actually does it free hand in different colors. they are beautiful and very very reasonable. i think a mug was $8usd, to me it is the best souvenir shop in all of dubai given that most of the pashimas, etc. are from india.
hope your hotel is near a metro stop. as i said, there is a lot of walking in dubai. hope this helps. any more specifics, if i can help you, i will answer.

column5:
entertainer is near enough always a good idea, especially if you're eating in high-end places, you can often cover the cost in one meal. for instance, i was pointing out yesterday, bice at hilton jumeirah has sea bass for around 220 aed, well gourmet is 195 aed and with the promo code edsd21 it comes in at 10% less, ie 175.50.
on top of that, there are 3 x vouchers for main courses (so up to six people can eat at once, and use 3 freebies or 2 people over 3 visits) as well as one for the brunch too.
if you're drinkers, do look at the cheers app too. don't overlook other decent promos on at the moment such as my emirates pass and marriott more cravings too.
chin chin!

column4:
started second hk arrival quarantine. november 2020 able pick hotel arrange meals. time (march 2021), designated quarantine hotel scheme 21 days quarantine meals provided hotel.
i wanted compare meal experiences designated quarantine hotels future trips hk friends family.
i staying mira moon. provide choices day meals breakfast, lunch dinner - local asian, international vegetarian. menu choices list 21 days stay sent upon booking, provided link day meal selections. meals must selected days advance fail select, hotel select me. early morning arrival flight selected lunch dinner day. last day quarantine stay, breakfast provided.
dessert provided lunch dinner, choice, daily dessert. idea experience far:
day lunch - stewed chicken red wine sauce, garlic spaghetti, corn bread roll mini croissant, steamed vegetables (carrots, broccoli, cauliflower), mini muffin icing dessert. meal served paper containers, cutlery thin wood disposable. chicken hard solid, somewhat expected bulk food preparation, garlic spaghetti flavourful, good amount vegetables, corn bread roll much corn bread roll slight corn taste, mini croissant good, hard mini muffin could taste sweet icing. main rectangular tray container separate compartments separate different foods keep everything looking nice neat, separate round containers bread dessert. overall, large filling portion size, fairly healthy good amount vegetables, good taste well presented. disposable wood cutlery difficult bend pressed knife took lot effort cut anything fork took multiple stabs pick pieces chicken.
day dinner - viennese fried pork filets fries ketchup tartar sauce, cucumber salad fish roe salad sauce topping, bread roll mini-croissant, dessert kind custard cream topped ground peanuts topping. pork filet pieces quite good, fat lean tough. fries oily. salad good. again, using disposable wood knife cut pork pieces real effort.
column5:
i just started my second hk arrival quarantine. my first was in november 2020 and i was able to pick any hotel and arrange my own meals. this time (march 2021), i am under the designated quarantine hotel scheme with 21 days quarantine and 3 meals provided by the hotel.
i wanted to compare meal experiences at designated quarantine hotels for future trips back to hk for myself and friends and family.
i am staying at mira moon. they provide 3 choices for each day for each of the 3 meals of breakfast, lunch and dinner - local asian, international and vegetarian. the menu choices list for all 21 days of my stay was sent to me upon booking, and i was provided with a link for each day to make my meal selections. meals must be selected 5 days in advance and if i fail to select, the hotel would select for me. i had a very early morning arrival flight so i selected lunch and dinner for the first day. for the last day of the quarantine stay, only breakfast is provided.
dessert is provided with lunch and dinner, but no choice, just the daily dessert. to give you an idea of the experience so far:
day 1 lunch - stewed chicken in red wine sauce, garlic spaghetti, corn bread roll and mini croissant, steamed vegetables (carrots, broccoli, cauliflower), mini muffin with icing dessert. meal served in paper containers, cutlery is thin wood disposable. chicken a bit hard and solid, somewhat expected in bulk food preparation, garlic spaghetti really flavourful, good amount of vegetables, corn bread roll not much like corn bread and more like a roll with a slight corn taste, mini croissant good, hard to say what the mini muffin is as all i could taste was the sweet icing. the main rectangular tray container had 4 separate compartments to separate the different foods and keep everything looking nice and neat, and there were separate round containers for the bread and dessert. overall, large filling portion size, fairly healthy with good amount of vegetables, good taste and well presented. the disposable wood cutlery is difficult to use as they bend when pressed so the knife took a lot of effort to cut anything and the fork took multiple stabs to pick up pieces of chicken.
day 1 dinner - viennese fried pork filets with fries with ketchup and tartar sauce, cucumber salad with fish roe and salad sauce topping, bread roll and mini-croissant, dessert was some kind of custard cream topped with ground up peanuts topping. pork filet pieces were quite good, had some fat so not too lean and tough. fries were not oily. salad good. again, using disposable wood knife to cut the pork pieces was a real effort.

column4:
i’m looking visit dubai time ever march 2022; assuming pandemic time. long way, head start. looking staying days two seasons hotel & apartments al sufouh (near palm jumeirah) due near metro rail station prefer cooking meals instead eating everyday.
i’m 48, active i’ll traveling myself. arriving (middle country). looking several flights uae. united stops (washington, dc & zurich), delta stops (atlanta & amsterdam) emirates (nonstop). third option require fly separate airline city emirates serves second options lets fly local area. flight times, emirates flies nonstop, example, ny dubai 12 1/2 hrs united offers 1/2hrs was, 8hrs zurich & 6hrs dubai, delta offers 2hrs atlanta, 1/2 hrs amsterdam & 1/2hrs dubai. return same, longer. unfortunately, i’m keen long hours flying (the longest flew 1/2 hrs, wasn’t bad though). granted, went long drive several years ago, drove 12 hrs. i’m thinking tolerate long drive, tolerate long hours flying. suck fly emirates options? advice appreciated.
column5:
i’m looking to visit dubai for the first time ever on march 2022; assuming this pandemic be over by that time. i know it is a long way, but i like to get a head start. looking at staying for 7 days at the two seasons hotel & apartments at al sufouh (near palm jumeirah) due to it being near metro rail station and prefer cooking meals instead of eating out everyday.
i’m 48, active and i’ll be traveling by myself. arriving from us (middle of the country). looking at several flights to uae. first being united with 2 stops (washington, dc & zurich), delta with 2 stops (atlanta & amsterdam) and emirates (nonstop). the third option will require me to fly on a separate airline to a city in which emirates serves while the first and second options lets me fly out of my local area. as for flight times, emirates flies nonstop, for example, ny to dubai in 12 1/2 hrs while united offers 2 1/2hrs to was, 8hrs to zurich & 6hrs to dubai, delta offers 2hrs to atlanta, 8 1/2 hrs to amsterdam & 6 1/2hrs to dubai. the return is the same, but longer. unfortunately, i’m not too keen of very long hours of flying (the longest i flew was 6 1/2 hrs, which wasn’t all too bad though). granted, i went on a long drive several years ago, which i drove for 12 hrs. i’m thinking if i can tolerate the long drive, then i can tolerate the long hours of flying. should i just suck it on up and fly emirates or just use either the other options? advice appreciated.

column4: airport express train central hk island. bus peak. spend couple hours there. come ride tram causeway bay. dim sum lunch dim sum palaces. try avoid office lunch hour (around pm). much street food hk. central, tram subway (mtr). ride star ferry kowloon. walk tsim sha tsui area. afternoon tea big hotels. airport express airport (take taxi kowloon station catch train).
column5: airport express train to central on hk island. take bus up to the peak. spend a couple of hours there. come back down and ride the tram to causeway bay. have dim sum for lunch at one of the dim sum palaces. try to avoid office lunch hour (around 1 pm). not much street food in hk. back to central, either the tram again or subway (mtr). ride the star ferry to kowloon. walk around the tsim sha tsui area. do an afternoon tea at one of the big hotels. take airport express back to the airport (take a taxi to the kowloon station to catch the train).

column4:
fly tokyo, spend days start moving chubu (central region japan's main island). i'd stop nagano days visit monkey park, sightseeing nagano station, drop matsumoto castle wasabi farm!
here's info wasabi farm: 
on way monkey park, i'll stop town called obuse chestnut dessert interested ukiyo-e art. 
then matsumoto, discounted bus tickets shirakawago, takayama, kamikochi, kanazawa. 
from kanazawa, i'd bullet train high-speed bus kyoto/osaka. i'd stay osaka instead kyoto cos hotels kyoto usually expensive. couple days city i'd extend trip cities close osaka himeji okayama.
himeji castle ranked best castle japan highly recommended. forget drop garden next cos beautiful. 
and time, visit mt. shosha himeji gives view. 
in okayama, okayama castle garden korakuen. 
lastly, kurashiki bikan quarter spot drop known little venice japan! 
i fill whole month. hopefully, info enough plan. info leave comments fill contact form :)
column5:
i would probably fly into tokyo, spend a few days there and start moving to chubu (central region of japan's main island). i'd stop by nagano for few days to visit the monkey park, sightseeing around nagano station, and drop by matsumoto for the castle and the wasabi farm!
here's more info about the wasabi farm: 
on the way to the monkey park, i'll also stop by a town called obuse for its chestnut dessert and if you are interested in ukiyo-e art. 
then from matsumoto, i will use one of the discounted bus tickets to get to shirakawago, takayama, kamikochi, and then kanazawa. 
from kanazawa, i'd take a bullet train or high-speed bus to kyoto/osaka. i'd probably stay in osaka instead of kyoto cos the hotels in kyoto are usually more expensive. a couple of days in each city and i'd also extend my trip to cities close to osaka such as himeji and okayama.
himeji castle was ranked the best castle in japan so highly recommended. and don't forget to drop by its garden just next to it cos is beautiful. 
and if you have time, you can also visit mt. shosha in himeji that gives you a great view. 
in okayama, there is okayama castle and its garden korakuen. 
lastly, kurashiki bikan quarter is a great spot to drop by as it is known as the little venice of japan! 
i think the above should fill up your whole month. and hopefully, the info is enough for you to plan. you can always get more info if you leave comments or fill out the contact form :)

column4:
regarding kamikochi visit, book night time bus leaving tokyo/shinjuku. bus arrive taisho pond sunrise. many people sunrise pond breathtaking. i'd recommend staying overnight kamikochi arrive early morning, catch last bus leaving kamikochi matsumoto. catch public transport jigokutani park. article kamikochi reference.

also, time matsumoto, love visit daio wasabi farm. late cherry blossom, place visit. refer article details.
column5:
regarding your kamikochi visit, you can book a night time bus leaving tokyo/shinjuku. the bus will arrive taisho pond around 5 which may be before sunrise. this is what many people are after because the sunrise at the pond is just breathtaking. i'd recommend staying overnight at kamikochi if you can but if you arrive in the early morning, you can catch the last bus leaving kamikochi at around 3 pm to matsumoto. from there you can then catch public transport to jigokutani park. below is an article about kamikochi for your reference.

also, if you have time in matsumoto, we love our visit to the daio wasabi farm. may may be too late for the cherry blossom, but it's still a great place to visit. you can refer to this article for more details.

column4:
food cheap expensive. mentioned mind spending more, budget 1,500 2,000 yen lunch per 2,000 4,000 yen dinner, figures per person. course, sky limit. numbers average decide splurge occasionally. consume 800 yen bowl ramen lunch pay 10,000 yen yakiniku evening.
what shops (say pizza express vs gordon ramsay) affect amount spend. chain sushi shops offer filling set meals 2,000 3,000 yen. high-end sushi places likely start 5,000 yen lunch 10,000 yen dinner. yakiniku (grill meat) popular choice wide range prices. again, lunch sets less 2,000 yen. top end beef places ginza cost much more.
sightseeing cost: admission fees found online exact yen. japan guide's relevant pages information: 
within tokyo, allow 1,000 yen transport daily per person.
edited: 10:45 pm, april 21,
column5:
food can be very cheap or very expensive. since you mentioned you don't mind spending a bit more, i suggest you budget 1,500 to 2,000 yen for lunch per and around 2,000 to 4,000 yen for dinner, all figures per person. of course, the sky is the limit. these numbers are average if you decide to splurge occasionally. you can consume a 800 yen bowl of ramen for lunch and then pay 10,000 yen for yakiniku in the evening.
what shops (say pizza express vs gordon ramsay) you go to also affect the amount you spend. chain sushi shops offer filling set meals for 2,000 to 3,000 yen. high-end sushi places are more likely to start at 5,000 yen for lunch and around 10,000 yen for dinner. yakiniku (grill meat) is another popular choice that has a wide range of prices. again, you can get lunch sets for less than 2,000 yen. the top end beef places at ginza will cost you much more.
sightseeing cost: admission fees can be found online to the exact yen. japan guide's relevant pages also has such information: 
within tokyo, allow 1,000 yen for transport daily per person.

column5:
barry - i promised to come back. it looks like your uk thread had disappeared and this one re-opened so i will put my lancashire recommendations here. none of them are far from manchester anyway.
the best food in the county s mark birchall's 2 michelin star food at moor hall in aughton. absolutely wonderful food but the one time we were there i found the atmosphere a bit clinical and we prefer lisa goodwin-allen's 1 star cooking at northcote, which comes complete with a fabulous atmosphere, especially the wine evenings, which i greatly miss. i suspect that northcote is not far from a second star.
moor hall has the barn attached to it for a more relaxed and cheaper option, although still high quality cooking
tom parker at the white swan at fence is the other michelin starred place in the county and is different again - very relaxed dining in a former pub which sill looks and feels like a pub.
other places with high quality cooking are hipping hall near kirkby lonsdale, the inn at whitewell and the freemasons arms at wiswell. i hear great things of the parkers arms at newton-by-bowland but haven't been. finally 263 in central preston opened in 2019 and was a real star until the virus closed it and i hope it will survive.
at the cheaper more everyday level i enjoy fino tapas, the continental and tang in preston and san marco at much hoole. finally everyone should have a local go-to curry house and ours in the sangam in lostock hall. it couldn't be more different to moor hall but still excellent.

if you are looking for another day trip out of tokyo, then i highly recommend the geibikei gorge in iwate for the boat trip down the gorge. your boatman will even sign the traditional song on the boat!
for info in this article: 
from osaka to chubu area (shirakawago/takayama...etc), i would catch a train or bus to kanazawa. spend at least 1.5 days there and head to shirakawago for a couple of hours and arriving at takayama.
the below article has information about discounted bus tickets for you to use in the chubu area. we used the mitsuboshi kaidou three-star route option ticket by the way.

from takayama, you can take the bus to matsumoto with nohi bus with the mitsuboshi kaidou three-star route option ticket as well.
and in matsumoto, recommend you to drop by the daio wasabi farm for some real wasabi!

and you can take a bullet train back to tokyo if you are going to get a jr pass from matsumoto.
hope the above helps :)

column5:
i live in orange county, ca. there are a whole lot of japanese people living in and near la and oc. we have numerous japanese markets and they are very busy. of course, japanese food is so popular now and many non-japanese people shop at those markets as well.
like-wise there are countless japanese restaurants and some have japanese chefs. though, you'll encounter more korean or chinese sushi chefs than japanese ones. it's funny that korean/chinese sushi chefs almost always want to pretend they're japanese. in that kind of situation, i start talking in japanese and they get chagrined. they are ok in general but i still think sushi is better made by chefs trained in japan.
as for ramen, i'm not a fan. i dislike tonkotsu, especially. i much prefer soba and i make it at home (from dried soba noodle).
someone was talking about american heart association's sodium intake being 1,500mg/day. that is the recommendation for people with heart conditions and/or high blood pressure. healthy young people can take a lot more sodium per day without worrying about any bad effects. in fact, if you're physically active and sweat a lot, 1,500mg sodium intake per day is too low. a blood sodium level that is too low is a medical emergency.

column5:
district 1:

tân định ward:

suggested walk:

1. như lan bakery / bánh mì. (one of the oldest name in saigon); the main store is on hàm nghi blvd., near the bạch đằng wharf.
2. tân định market; best for fabrics and ready-made clothing; plenty of food kiosks and vendors around.
3. tân định pink church; a cute little church.
4. bánh xèo 46a đinh công tráng - put on the culinary map by a number of world-renowned chefs.
a wonderful selection on the menu with consistent quality and flavor; there's also an ac room if you can't stand the heat.
5. papaya salad with beef jerky on hai ba trung, across from the park; one of the most popular street vendors in the city.
6. the lê văn tám park.
7. trần hưng đạo temple; general thd was arguably the greatest general in vn history, especially in naval history. the bạch đằng wharf was named after one of his greatest naval battles. his most prominent statue was placed at the roundabout near the waterbus station

8. jade pagoda (điện ngọc hoàng), where ex-president obama once visited.
9. longevity temple (chùa vạn thọ); one of the few pagodas along the canal.
hoàng sa, the canal road, is teeming with coffee shops and breakfast places in the morning, and a haven for beer and food in the late afternoon into the late, late evening.
10. a true vegetarian place, for those with such a lifestyle.
the area boasts plenty of good eats, including authentic vietnamese and french cuisine.
i'll get to them when i have some time.
cheers,
john

column5:
hi nishin91,
good to know that you're planning a summer trip to hokkaido.
based on your criteria, i'd suggest
1. lake side resort suimeikaku - a small onsen hotel with about 10 rooms along the lake rim of shikotsu-ko, about 30 min drive from cts (shin-chitose airport). in our stay in july 2018, most were adults. it serves italian dinner.
2. the windsor hotel toya resort - was once the venue of g7/8 meeting overlooking the beautiful and serene toya-ko. have no experience though would love to stay there when japan re-opens its border. there used to be a michelin 2-star french restaurant though not sure about the latest status.
should you be heading to biei/furano, i have more recommendations.
happy planning.
my summer trip in hokkaido, staying in toya-ko and shikotsu-ko.

column5:
***addendum march 2021***
i made a couple of posts a few years ago recommending this company.
however, they’ve recently changed their policy and i want to change my review to say that, sadly, i can’t recommend sushi wifi anymore.
do not use this sim data provider. avoid.
the reasons as follows:
the reason being, for months now, my sushi wifi data speed was 0.01- 0.02mbps. literally slower than dial-up.
i called sushi and they sent me another sim. same issue... super crazy slow speeds. totally unusable internet. google news page takes a minute to load. forget youtube or any streaming.
after over a month of this (i had to buy another data sim at bic), they send me an email, saying that the unlimited wifi is now limited to 100gb a month, and if you use over that, the speed will be limited (in my case to 0.01-0.02mbps)
the internet will remain at an totally unusable data speed until the next month!
it would have been good if they’d told me this earlier but they didn’t. until a couple months later. so i was using over 100gb and had no internet basically, until the next month.
cost is still the same, even they’ve limited the data now, so price is now pretty high given that the data is effectively capped at 100gb a month ~8000 jpy/month. it’s not unlimited data internet, because once you hit 100gb, the data speed is throttled to basically zero until next month.
because of this, i can’t recommend them. just go and buy a data limited card for (3 x 30gb a fortnight). it’ll be cheaper or same price, and your speed won’t be throttled to near zero if you use over the data.
i’ve had good experience with sushi in the past, but unfortunately, i can’t honestly recommend them anymore.
edited: 7:08 am, march 26, 2021

column4: understand interest kids clubs hour two highlight kids time massage time relax. kids clubs offer fantastic activities kids, learn balinese dancing, dress traditional clothing, art work, cooking decorating cookies options lot fun kids, able play kids kids clubs reason them. staff interest kids. . sanur, prama sanur beach hotel best choice. family pool area, small kids water play area family cabanas. (please see photos understand offer) beach front. consider villa ubud nusa lembongan. stick padma legian want walk waterbom park places mentioned earlier question. nusa lembongan stay nights add night elsewhere. mara river lodge & safari park mentioned worth adding holiday. nusa lembongan done day trip save moving again. much see bali given short amount time lose lot time moving hotel next. add days trip grab opportunity.
column5: i can understand the interest in kids clubs as even an hour or two can be a highlight for the kids and give you time for a massage or the time to relax. some kids clubs offer fantastic activities for the kids, they can learn balinese dancing, dress up in traditional clothing, make art work, cooking and decorating cookies the options are a lot of fun for the kids, being able to play with the other kids in the kids clubs is another reason to use them. the staff really take and interest in the kids. . in sanur, prama sanur beach hotel may be your best choice. the family pool is a great area, with a small kids water play area and family cabanas. (please see photos to understand what is on offer) and this is beach front. i would consider a villa for ubud or nusa lembongan. and stick with the padma in legian or if you want to walk to waterbom park go for the places i mentioned in your earlier question. i would suggest if you go to nusa lembongan to stay 2 nights and add a night elsewhere. the mara river lodge & safari park as mentioned is worth adding to your holiday. nusa lembongan can also be done as a day trip and would save you moving again. there is so much to see and do in bali and given the short amount of time you have you lose a lot of time moving from one hotel to the next. if you can add a few more days to your trip grab the opportunity.

column5:
hi everyone. we have flight vouchers that have to be used by march 2022 and so thinking about using them to fly from sfo to tokyo over the christmas holiday when our hs junior son and hs freshman daughter are out of school. understanding that covid could still throw a wrench into things, we thought that we would get our travel bug by doing some research/planning.
we would leave sfo on sat. dec 18 and arrive narita afternoon dec 19. spend one night in tokyo and then take the first train we can down to hiroshima. spend dec 20/21 there to see hiroshima and miyajima.
leave dec 22 am for kyoto. how long of a stay is recommended in kyoto?
after kyoto should we go straight to tokyo or do we also stop in osaka?
we have read about the packed trains leaving tokyo on/about december 29 and so we were thinking that we would end up back in tokyo before december 29 and then fly out from there on january 2.
given that amount of time, what do you all recommend for stays at each place. as for things to do, we definitely want to see the tokyo fish market. what about the go-karts in tokyo? sounds crazy but the kids would probably love it? is a bike tour in kyoto worth it? the family loves sushi and ramen and so amazing sushi and ramen recommendations are welcome.
thanks in advance.

great to know. that's why one should never assume. for example, when i travel to italy, i don't go looking for pasta done the hong kong way either.
it also reminds me of another experience when i visited vienna years ago. we got sick of eating schnitzel, tafelspitz and potatoes for so many days that we opted for a japanese restaurant once. we got rolls the size bigger than my fist. there were some japanese tourists eating there as well and they were mumbling things didn't look right. we should have stuck with local food!
>>>as for sushi, i’ll try not to be offended about the california role and avocado comments... :). we are a chinese family of four with two kids who love real sushi and have eaten in many hole in the wall places in hong kong; the more snake the better... :)
as to your vouchers, if they don't work out, it seems that europe is going to open faster. of course, who knows whether the covid cases will bounce back. all countries opening now are taking unknown risks.

column5:
hi, i'm on day #8 of my quarantine, so thought i would provide a little insight.
my asq is maple hotel in bang na. i'm in the basic room, cost is 33k. overall i'm very satisfied with my choice.
room: the room itself is quite spacious for 1 person. i have some workout videos on my laptop and there was just enough space for that. it's a basic room, not elegant, but clean, quiet and functional. there is a medium size fridge that i've made good use of because my gf kindly delivered a large care package of fruit and salads. the ac works fine and is quiet. the room also has a very good workspace and quality chair (this is important to me as some of the other asq's that i considered did not). wifi has been very dependable - there is a router in each room as well as ethernet cable. i did have some issues early on but it turned out to be an issue specific to my room and they promptly sent a technician to resolve it. they also lent me an ethernet adapter as my computer does not have a rj45 port. i was going to order from lazada, so when i asked if that was allowed, they said yes, but also mentioned they could lend me one. so big +1 for helpful service.
food: one thing i found out in doing my dd, is that some asq's do not have their own kitchen and rely on an outside caterer. as a result food choices are very limited (or nil) and there is no choice on timing. maple on the other hand prepares everything in-house and the choices are wide (about 20 choices for lunch/dinner). there is also about a 4 hour time window for each meal and you can request preferred times. so while i would rate the food as just "decent", the fact there is a broad choice and you can specify the time is a big positive. the food was never cold, often luke warm and sometimes piping hot (there are about 4 pasta choices and i think because the containers are filled to the brim, these were always nice and hot). the one negative i would say about the food is lack of vegatables. even off of the vegetarian menu (vegatables and rice for example), the vegatables were fried in oil and not that appealing. most dishes had just a slice of cucumber/tomatoe as garnish. luckily my gf brought me salads, without this i think i might contract scurvy lol.
getting outside: covid test was day 5 and got my negative result around 10:00 am the following day so i was able to leave my room on day 6. officially you are allowed 1 hr outside your room but this is not really enforced. i think the limit is just in place so that the outside areas don't get over-crowded. maple has quite large rooftop areas on each of the 3 towers with a capacity of 16, but there were typically only 3-4 people there at a time, so i think you could spend as much time up there as you like. also they had a different system depending on whether you were from a high risk country (us is in this group for sure and i assume uk). high riskers had black/brown/white wrist bands and others had orange/yellow/green. i believe that the high risk group are not allowed out of their room until after the second covid test.
balcony: this seems to be a big factor in choosing asq's (it was for me). all maple rooms have balconies usuable from day 0. i was wondering if perhaps this was over-rated, but now having been here i have to say having a balcony was a big plus, especially in the days that you are stuck in your room. even though my view was non-existent (i faced the other tower), it was still nice to put my chair out in the morning, brew my lavazza with my french press and sit out there while the temp was still pleasant.
staff: all very friendly, though most interaction is with the line app - both with the hotel and hospital (to report body temperature).
one negative for some people is that maple does not allow deliveries from 7-11. for me this is no big deal, as unlike just about everybody else, i rarely go to 7-11! there is one in my neighbourhood at home - in 20 years i've never gone in lol. i did bring my own snacks, coffee, tea etc and my gf can bring me anything else.
if i were to do it over, i would likely choose maple again. though if i were with my gf or other family members, i'd be inclined to go up a notch, but for a single low maintenace guy, maple is just fine.
cheers
edited: 10:18 pm, january 30, 2021

hello all and thank you for reading.
i am 67 years old, fairly well travelled but have not been to indonesia (yet).
next october, 2022, i am considering spending a month in bali. two weeks volunteering in ubud teaching kindergarten and primary school. the week prior and the week after will be spent travelling around.
i hear mixed reviews of bali. i know that nothing is the way it was 10 or 20 years ago. 'tourists have ruined the place' is common on so many destinations around the world.
but, for those of you who have been recently, what is your opinion? and i know everyone has an opinion and i will listen to all the good and bad.
i have never been so have nothing to compare to the 'way it was'. i also know, like thailand , laos and other destinations in asia there are those places that have the 'full moon parties' and predominantly young people wanting to drink and have fun
i will most likely not be going to those places, my idea of fun has changed over the years :)
i am looking for great snorkelling, beautiful scenery, temples, small villages great food , meeting people and local vibe. i am unfortunately not able to do difficult hiking anymore, but some easier ones would be most welcome.
i am hoping my friend of the same vintage will join me, although i could be by myself which is fine too.
my husband will meet me after wards in thailand for the month of november.
so......what is your opinion? has it lost its charm, too commercial, too crazy busy?
i am going to be speaking with the company on sunday to ask more questions about the volunteer part ( i have taught english in other volunteer settings in asia and africa before).
any imput of your experience would be most appreciated. thank you so much .( please be kind ) :)

column5: most hotels in israel do not have meat as part of their breakfast buffet since if they are kosher, they cannot serve milk and meat together. however, there is a huge buffet of cheeses, breads, cereals, yoghourts, halvas, cakes, salads, egg dishes (e.g. shakshuka, omelettes, etc), and often other freshly made freshly pancakes, waffles, etc

column5:
at the end of 2019 we stayed at an airbnb property in marina. it was a mixed experience. from a value point of view it was outstanding. we had a lot of space for a family of four and enjoyed being able to cook our own food. we had all the amenities we needed as if we were living at home.
however, the property wasn't managed by the host. he left it to the reception staff at the tower to sort out issues. there was some black mould on some ceilings. the showers/baths leaked water onto the floor as the sealed were either worn or didn't exist!
basically, it was difficult to get things sorted out in a timely manner, so that ruined part of the holiday for us.
next time we will just book multiple hotel rooms as it's easier to get on with enjoying the holiday.
